# 1. MongoDB Service Commands

These commands are used to manage the MongoDB server process on Linux systems using `systemd`.

---

## Start MongoDB Service

Starts the MongoDB database server.

```bash
sudo systemctl start mongod
```

Use this command when MongoDB is installed but not currently running.

---

## Stop MongoDB Service

Stops the running MongoDB server safely.

```bash
sudo systemctl stop mongod
```

Useful before system maintenance or configuration changes.

---

## Restart MongoDB Service

Restarts the MongoDB server.

```bash
sudo systemctl restart mongod
```

Usually required after editing MongoDB configuration files.

---

## Check MongoDB Status

Shows whether MongoDB is active, stopped, or failed.

```bash
sudo systemctl status mongod
```

Example output may include:

- Active state
- Process ID
- Memory usage
- Startup logs

---

## Enable MongoDB on Boot

Automatically starts MongoDB whenever Linux boots.

```bash
sudo systemctl enable mongod
```

